        "creation_date": 1269867899,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "Spring MVC Best Practice Handling Unrecoverable Exceptions In Controller",
        "body": "<p>When you have a controller that does logic with services and DAO's that may throw an unrecoverable exception, what is the best practice in dealing with those method calls?<\/p>\n\n<p>Currently an app I'm working on has very lengthy try catch methods that simply err.out exception messages, this doesn't seem very robust and I think that this code smells, is there any cookie cutter best practice for handling this in spring-mvc?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 2538031,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "exception",
            "spring-mvc"
        ],
        "score": 3,
        "accepted_answer_id": 2538082,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 4856,
        "last_edit_date": 1269868202
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c11c60c7e6d29cb4b87f3c0a3b692181?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 3001,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4249,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4249/matt-b",
                "reputation": 140375,
                "display_name": "matt b",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 8,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1348648204,
            "creation_date": 1269868194,
            "body": "<p>Don't catch the Exception and allow it to bubble up to a <a href=\"http://static.springsource.org/spring/docs/3.1.x/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/HandlerExceptionResolver.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">HandlerExceptionResolver<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can supply a <a href=\"http://static.springsource.org/spring/docs/3.1.x/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/servlet/handler/SimpleMappingExceptionResolver.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">SimpleMappingExceptionResolver<\/a> in your applicationContext to map certain exception types (or all) to a view name (such as \"errorpage\"). Or if you need more complex logic, you can supply your own implementation.<\/p>\n\n<p>This way your code isn't concerned with Exceptions that it can't handle in the first place, and you can make sure that your users see a nice \"Oops something happened, don't worry we're on it\" page instead of a stacktrace.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2538058,
            "question_id": 2538031,
            "last_edit_date": 1348648204
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/256428da533157429934eeccb259aadc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 112952,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 297762,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/297762/robby-pond",
                "reputation": 73524,
                "display_name": "Robby Pond",
                "accept_rate": 87
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1269868350,
            "creation_date": 1269868350,
            "body": "<p>Check out the <a href=\"http://static.springsource.org/spring/docs/3.0.x/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/bind/annotation/ExceptionHandler.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">@ExceptionHandler<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>You can use it like<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>@ExceptionHandler(IOException.class)\n@ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR)\npublic void handleExc(IOException ext) {}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>That would catch all IOExceptions thrown by the controller method and write out a 500 to the response.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2538082,
            "question_id": 2538031
        }
    ],
